<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n10076a"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n10" href="#n10076a">N10 (VI.B.16)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n10all.htm#n10076a"> 76(a)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> letter in hare</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Harpage envoie &agrave; Cyrus un message dangereux dans le corps d&apos;un li&egrave;vre1. <font color="green">[Harpagius sent Cyrus a dangerous message in the body of a hare.]</font> H&eacute;rod. &ldquo;Comme les chemins &eacute;taient gard&eacute;s, Harpage ne put trouver d&apos;autre exp&eacute;dient que celui-ci. S&apos;&eacute;tant fait apporter un <mark>li&egrave;vre</mark>, il ouvrit le ventre de cet animal d&apos;une mani&egrave;re adroite, y mit une lettre, et, l&apos;ayant ensuite recousu, le confia au plus fid&egrave;le de ses domestiques, et lui dit de le porter &agrave; Cyrus, en lui recommandant de l&apos;ouvrir lui-m&ecirc;me et sans t&eacute;moins.&rdquo; Clio, I, 123. <font color="green">[Herod. &ldquo;As the roads were guarded. Harpagius could not find any expedient other than this. A hare was brought to him and he opened the belly of the animal in a skilful manner and placed a letter inside it. He then sewed it up again and entrusted it to his most faithful servant, telling him to bring it to Cyrus and enjoining him to open it up himself, without witnesses.&rdquo; ]</font> <small> Arthur de Rothschild, <a name="ARHD" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#ARHD"><cite title="source">Histoire de la poste</cite></a> (1876) 22</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
